\title{Astropy}

\taxon{skill}

\meta{description}{Comprehensive Python library for astronomy and astrophysics. This skill should be used when working with astronomical data including celestial coordinates, physical units, FITS files, cosmological calculations, time systems, tables, world coordinate systems (WCS), and astronomical data analysis. Use when tasks involve coordinate transformations, unit conversions, FITS file manipulation, cosmological distance calculations, time scale conversions, or astronomical data processing.}

\subtree{
\title{Astropy}
\subtree{
\title{Overview}
\p{Astropy is the core Python package for astronomy, providing essential functionality for astronomical research and data analysis. Use astropy for coordinate transformations, unit and quantity calculations, FITS file operations, cosmological calculations, precise time handling, tabular data manipulation, and astronomical image processing.}
}

\subtree{
\title{When to Use This Skill}
\p{Use astropy when tasks involve:}

\ul{
\li{Converting between celestial coordinate systems (ICRS, Galactic, FK5, AltAz, etc.)}
\li{Working with physical units and quantities (converting Jy to mJy, parsecs to km, etc.)}
\li{Reading, writing, or manipulating FITS files (images or tables)}
\li{Cosmological calculations (luminosity distance, lookback time, Hubble parameter)}
\li{Precise time handling with different time scales (UTC, TAI, TT, TDB) and formats (JD, MJD, ISO)}
\li{Table operations (reading catalogs, cross-matching, filtering, joining)}
\li{WCS transformations between pixel and world coordinates}
\li{Astronomical constants and calculations}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Quick Start}
\pre{\startverb
import astropy.units as u
from astropy.coordinates import SkyCoord
from astropy.time import Time
from astropy.io import fits
from astropy.table import Table
from astropy.cosmology import Planck18

# Units and quantities
distance = 100 * u.pc
distance_km = distance.to(u.km)

# Coordinates
coord = SkyCoord(ra=10.5*u.degree, dec=41.2*u.degree, frame='icrs')
coord_galactic = coord.galactic

# Time
t = Time('2023-01-15 12:30:00')
jd = t.jd  # Julian Date

# FITS files
data = fits.getdata('image.fits')
header = fits.getheader('image.fits')

# Tables
table = Table.read('catalog.fits')

# Cosmology
d_L = Planck18.luminosity_distance(z=1.0)
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Core Capabilities}
\subtree{
\title{1. Units and Quantities (\code{\startverb astropy.units\stopverb})}
\p{Handle physical quantities with units, perform unit conversions, and ensure dimensional consistency in calculations.}

\p{\strong{Key operations:}}

\ul{
\li{Create quantities by multiplying values with units}
\li{Convert between units using \code{\startverb .to()\stopverb} method}
\li{Perform arithmetic with automatic unit handling}
\li{Use equivalencies for domain-specific conversions (spectral, doppler, parallax)}
\li{Work with logarithmic units (magnitudes, decibels)}
}

\p{\strong{See:} \code{\startverb references/units.md\stopverb} for comprehensive documentation, unit systems, equivalencies, performance optimization, and unit arithmetic.}
}

\subtree{
\title{2. Coordinate Systems (\code{\startverb astropy.coordinates\stopverb})}
\p{Represent celestial positions and transform between different coordinate frames.}

\p{\strong{Key operations:}}

\ul{
\li{Create coordinates with \code{\startverb SkyCoord\stopverb} in any frame (ICRS, Galactic, FK5, AltAz, etc.)}
\li{Transform between coordinate systems}
\li{Calculate angular separations and position angles}
\li{Match coordinates to catalogs}
\li{Include distance for 3D coordinate operations}
\li{Handle proper motions and radial velocities}
\li{Query named objects from online databases}
}

\p{\strong{See:} \code{\startverb references/coordinates.md\stopverb} for detailed coordinate frame descriptions, transformations, observer-dependent frames (AltAz), catalog matching, and performance tips.}
}

\subtree{
\title{3. Cosmological Calculations (\code{\startverb astropy.cosmology\stopverb})}
\p{Perform cosmological calculations using standard cosmological models.}

\p{\strong{Key operations:}}

\ul{
\li{Use built-in cosmologies (Planck18, WMAP9, etc.)}
\li{Create custom cosmological models}
\li{Calculate distances (luminosity, comoving, angular diameter)}
\li{Compute ages and lookback times}
\li{Determine Hubble parameter at any redshift}
\li{Calculate density parameters and volumes}
\li{Perform inverse calculations (find z for given distance)}
}

\p{\strong{See:} \code{\startverb references/cosmology.md\stopverb} for available models, distance calculations, time calculations, density parameters, and neutrino effects.}
}

\subtree{
\title{4. FITS File Handling (\code{\startverb astropy.io.fits\stopverb})}
\p{Read, write, and manipulate FITS (Flexible Image Transport System) files.}

\p{\strong{Key operations:}}

\ul{
\li{Open FITS files with context managers}
\li{Access HDUs (Header Data Units) by index or name}
\li{Read and modify headers (keywords, comments, history)}
\li{Work with image data (NumPy arrays)}
\li{Handle table data (binary and ASCII tables)}
\li{Create new FITS files (single or multi-extension)}
\li{Use memory mapping for large files}
\li{Access remote FITS files (S3, HTTP)}
}

\p{\strong{See:} \code{\startverb references/fits.md\stopverb} for comprehensive file operations, header manipulation, image and table handling, multi-extension files, and performance considerations.}
}

\subtree{
\title{5. Table Operations (\code{\startverb astropy.table\stopverb})}
\p{Work with tabular data with support for units, metadata, and various file formats.}

\p{\strong{Key operations:}}

\ul{
\li{Create tables from arrays, lists, or dictionaries}
\li{Read/write tables in multiple formats (FITS, CSV, HDF5, VOTable)}
\li{Access and modify columns and rows}
\li{Sort, filter, and index tables}
\li{Perform database-style operations (join, group, aggregate)}
\li{Stack and concatenate tables}
\li{Work with unit-aware columns (QTable)}
\li{Handle missing data with masking}
}

\p{\strong{See:} \code{\startverb references/tables.md\stopverb} for table creation, I/O operations, data manipulation, sorting, filtering, joins, grouping, and performance tips.}
}

\subtree{
\title{6. Time Handling (\code{\startverb astropy.time\stopverb})}
\p{Precise time representation and conversion between time scales and formats.}

\p{\strong{Key operations:}}

\ul{
\li{Create Time objects in various formats (ISO, JD, MJD, Unix, etc.)}
\li{Convert between time scales (UTC, TAI, TT, TDB, etc.)}
\li{Perform time arithmetic with TimeDelta}
\li{Calculate sidereal time for observers}
\li{Compute light travel time corrections (barycentric, heliocentric)}
\li{Work with time arrays efficiently}
\li{Handle masked (missing) times}
}

\p{\strong{See:} \code{\startverb references/time.md\stopverb} for time formats, time scales, conversions, arithmetic, observing features, and precision handling.}
}

\subtree{
\title{7. World Coordinate System (\code{\startverb astropy.wcs\stopverb})}
\p{Transform between pixel coordinates in images and world coordinates.}

\p{\strong{Key operations:}}

\ul{
\li{Read WCS from FITS headers}
\li{Convert pixel coordinates to world coordinates (and vice versa)}
\li{Calculate image footprints}
\li{Access WCS parameters (reference pixel, projection, scale)}
\li{Create custom WCS objects}
}

\p{\strong{See:} \code{\startverb references/wcs_and_other_modules.md\stopverb} for WCS operations and transformations.}
}
}

